\subsection{Crystal structures with low $E_{\mathbf{m}}$}
We summarize the $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ values of the $F m \overline{3} \mathrm{~m}$ and the $P 4_{2} / \mathrm{nmc}$ structures obtained herein and in former computational studies $^{42,47-50}$ in Table 5. Former computational studies have mainly used the GGA, rather than the GGA+U. To compare the results, we also employ the GGA with the PBE form. ${ }^{33}$ The $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ values obtained herein using the GGA are almost the same as those mentioned in previous computational reports. The $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ values obtained using the GGA+U are larger than those obtained using the GGA for both the $F m \overline{3} m$ and $P 4_{2} / n m c$ structures.

We also compare the $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ values of $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{0}\right)$ and $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{2+}\right)$. Table 5 shows that the $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ values of $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{0}\right)$ are much larger than those of $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{2+}\right)$, independent of the crystal structure and the exchangecorrelation functional. Larger $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ values for $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{0}\right)$ than for $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{2+}\right)$ have been reported in other oxides like $\mathrm{MgO}^{51}$ and $\mathrm{ZnO}^{52}$ When a $V_{\mathrm{O}}$ jumps into its nearest-neighboring $\mathrm{O}$ site, the $\mathrm{O}$ atom at the nearest-neighboring site migrates in the opposite direction. For $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{2+}\right)$, no occupied levels are present inside $E_{\mathrm{g}}$. On the other hand, for $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{0}\right)$, the two electrons occupying the deep level have transition into the conduction band when the moving $\mathrm{O}$ atom is in the transition state (center of the hopping path), ${ }^{47}$ which may need more energy for $V_{\mathrm{O}}$ hopping. Considering the abovementioned reasons, we employed $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{2+}\right)$ for the $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ in this study.

Hereafter, we will refer to the $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ obtained by the GGA+U calculations.

In the case of the initial-state structure for the CI-NEB method, we employed the relaxed supercell possessing a $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{2+}\right)$ having the lowest energy among the different $\mathrm{O}$ sites. For the 14 crystal structures of reoptimized- $\mathrm{ZrO}_{2}$ that have well-converged structures with a $\left(V_{\mathrm{O}}^{2+}\right)$, we considered various final-state structures that have the $V_{\mathrm{O}}$ at the nearest-neighboring $\mathrm{O}$ site with the cutoff distance of $3.5 \AA$ for the CI-NEB method (see Fig. S2 in ESI $\dagger$ ). Among the $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ values of different migration paths, the lowest value was extracted; we then checked whether the $V_{\mathrm{O}}$ could migrate to the original site in the nearestneighboring supercell via the one type of migration path with the lowest $E_{\mathrm{m}}$, because the migration of the $V_{\mathrm{O}}$ through the bulk system is practically meaningful. In 12 of the 14 crystal structures, $V_{\mathrm{O}}$ could migrate to the original site in the nearestneighboring supercell via the migration path with the lowest $E_{\mathrm{m}}$. However, for the $P 4 / n$ and $R \overline{3}$ structures, a $V_{\mathrm{O}}$ needs different paths with different $E_{\mathrm{m}}$ values to migrate to the\\
